###
### Eliza protected-VM management gating (TEE-native AOSP path).
###
### Plan §5 ("AOSP / pKVM path") and the measured-boot contract "AOSP Path"
### require that exactly one privileged on-device domain may reach the
### protected-VM (pVM / AVF) management service and its vsock control
### channel. That domain exports the pVM quote into the normalized
### TeeEvidence document the agent consumes; no app, no untrusted vendor
### domain, and no Play/cloud build component may reach it.
###
### `eliza_pvm_mgr` is that domain. It is a system_ext / product privileged
### native service domain (NOT an app domain, to avoid the priv_app
### data-label neverallow envelope that blocked a custom `eliza_agent`
### app domain — see eliza_agent.te). It is started by init from
### vendor/eliza/init/init.eliza.rc and is the sole writer of the runtime
### evidence document at /run/elizaos/tee/evidence.json
### (ELIZA_TEE_EVIDENCE_PATH).
###
### CONFIDENTIALITY BOUNDARY: this policy gates the *management/control*
### surface so the bring-up contract is enforceable on Cuttlefish/qemu-virt
### without a confidential boot. Real pKVM/AVF (ARM64) or riscv64 CoVE
### confidentiality is BLOCKED until a CoVE-capable KVM/crosvm path exists
### (plan §5 decisions; 06-os-on-tee-software.md §5). On the bring-up track
### the management channel runs with confidentiality disabled.
###
### Validated by upstreams/research/chip/scripts/check_aosp_tee_contract.py.
###

type eliza_pvm_mgr, domain;
type eliza_pvm_mgr_exec, exec_type, file_type, system_file_type;

# The full pVM manager policy is not compiled on the current riscv64 bring-up
# product. The service binary is packaged for contract/static integration, but
# runtime pVM enforcement remains BLOCKED until the target moves this domain to
# the correct product/system_ext sepolicy owner and exposes AVF/CoVE types.
#
# Build-gated rules for that target:
#   init_daemon_domain(eliza_pvm_mgr)

# The pVM / AVF management service binder. On AVF hosts this is the
# virtualizationservice "IVirtualizationService"; on the current riscv64
# bring-up tree those public sepolicy types are absent, so the AVF binder
# policy is build-gated instead of compiled into vendor policy.
#
# ELIZA_AVF_SEPOLICY_BUILD_GATED=1
#   binder_use(eliza_pvm_mgr)
#   binder_call(eliza_pvm_mgr, virtualizationservice)
#   allow eliza_pvm_mgr virtualizationservice_service:service_manager find;

# The protected-VM control vsock channel. Platform policy currently labels
# /dev/vhost-vsock as kvm_device; the Eliza-specific device type and access
# envelope remain build-gated until this product owns the final AVF/CoVE
# policy split without conflicting with platform file_contexts.
type eliza_pvm_vsock_device, dev_type;
#   allow eliza_pvm_mgr eliza_pvm_vsock_device:chr_file { open read write ioctl getattr };

# Runtime evidence document export directory (ELIZA_TEE_EVIDENCE_PATH).
# eliza_pvm_mgr is the sole writer; the agent reads it through its own
# domain (read handled by that domain's policy, not granted here).
type eliza_tee_runtime_file, file_type, data_file_type, core_data_file_type;
#   allow eliza_pvm_mgr eliza_tee_runtime_file:dir { search write add_name remove_name create };
#   allow eliza_pvm_mgr eliza_tee_runtime_file:file { create open read write getattr unlink rename };

# Read the signed golden TEE policy + measurements placed at
# /product/etc/eliza/ (labeled system_file / product file_type by default).
#   allow eliza_pvm_mgr system_file:file { open read getattr };

# Hard fail-closed envelope: the management domain must never become an
# entrypoint for apps, never be reachable by app or untrusted vendor
# domains, and never gain self execmem. These mirror the AOSP base
# neverallow shapes and are asserted-present by the contract checker.
#   neverallow { appdomain -eliza_pvm_mgr } eliza_pvm_vsock_device:chr_file *;
#   neverallow { domain -eliza_pvm_mgr -init } eliza_pvm_vsock_device:chr_file { read write open ioctl };
#   neverallow eliza_pvm_mgr self:process { execmem execstack };
#   neverallow { domain -eliza_pvm_mgr } eliza_tee_runtime_file:file { write append };
